This is not something I want to be proud of (well, still a little bit) as I’m not well placed to judge myself, but all these reactions from different people let me foresee that I still have a clue about our capacities.<br>
Being only 50th, and not part of a raiding guild, I won’t speak about high end raids but general things for the young ones.<br>
<br>
First thing is : why do you want to play a shaman ? Even more, what is the style of playing that you want to have ? I personnaly made a shaman for I wanted to be able to solo big things and be usefull to groups. This was reducing my choice of class range. Then I wanted to be able to get hit and still be in the face of mobs (sorry, I’m not the kind of root cooking shaman, though it is a really valid strategy). This was even more reducing the choice. Finally, I wanted to have several way of killing. This drove me to 2 classes : shaman and necro. While necro can be in the face of mobs and have more way of killing than shaman), I deleted my previous necro to make a shaman as one thing I really like is going into newbie zone and buff young ones like Hell and see their joy, this is something necro can’t do hehe. Of course, one thing that you have to keep in mind is that you MUST (yes, I said MUST) play a toon you like. I’ve done incredible things with just a SK 40 and me 47 and couldn’t do that same thing later with a full group ! Why ? Simply because the guy and I (who never met before) really enjoyed our classes and thus could reach our limits without going beyond them. Well, this last statement is obvious, but I still wanted to highlight it.<br>
<br>
The 2 second things are :<br>
-        don’t get discourage. The shaman class has some really hard levels to go through : before 24, from 29 to 34 (these where the worst) and 44-49 (well, I made them in 2 months, but I hardly logged during this time, so I’m maybe a bit biased here). Yes, there will be a lot of times when you will say “Sh.t, this bores me, I’m gonna reroll”. Don’t do that, keep with it, the rewards awaits you and I can tell you that being 50, I often feel like god amongst mobs.<br>
-        Know the other classes possibilities. This might seem obvious, but I still find some people saying “Hey, I didn’t know XXX class could do YYY !”. If you know the other possibilities, you will be better at enhancing their possibilities and fill in the blanks of your group. This will also sometime help you to build some strategy to do something you thought impossible as all class have some “useless” spells which combined can make unwaited results. So don’t be afraid to spend some time on classes sites to learn about them. I’ve found that the places where I could learn the most about some classes (but spell descriptions) are on the specialised forum.<br>
<br>
Now comes the life a shaman. I won’t make a guide for what to hunt, where and when, using any search engine on internet will bring you tons of stuff, though I want to bring a special note about the crucible which is a great source of information. You will find a lot of informations on castersrealm too, but be aware that some of them (especially some spell descriptions) are completely false.<br>
<br>
Now, what is a shaman ? Well, a shaman is a wonderfull toolbox for a party. We are one of those classes that are not specialised in anything (well, we do slow better than anyone, but chanters do that almost as good as us, and later, BST can land their slow more easily than us, but this is information I have from high level friends, well, very very high level friends). These classes (such as shaman or necro) can do almost anything, though not as good as specialized one. The advantage is that in any kind of group, we are usefull, filling in the gap of the party.<br>
<br>
One of our main utility in a group is that we enhance the fighting capacities of others. From this standpoint, the shaman is a twin of the enchanter. Having one in your group is a booster, but while enchanter boost capacities of casters (hey, they can do lotsa things beside that mind you), shaman boost the capacities of fighters.<br>
<br>
Here is a quick review of our spell lines :<br>
-        Stats enhancement. While I’m not sure these are that usefull, they still are. Str increases the attack value of someone, thus allowing him to hit more often and reaching is max damage more often. Dex increases the proc rate of weapon, skill increase and, some say, reduce fizzles on spells though I’ve never remark that. Agi slightly increases AC. STA means more hp and CHA means that when you will go sell your stuff, you will bring more money out of it that the average player (this is not true for me as, being an ogre, I started with a very low CHA). HP, AC and resists buffs : do I really need to explain more about them ?<br>
-        Regeneration and cannibalize. The first one will increase your hp regeneration rate, the second eats your life to give you mana. See the goal of both working together ?<br>
-        Debuffs. Slow will reduce the attack speed of mobs, thus reducing the damage your party will receive. This is, to my mind, the most debilitating effect one can put on a mob in EQ. Incapacitate line will reduce the fighting stats of your enemy (AC and STR mainly), allowing you to it them more easily and reducing (a little, but every little bit helps) the average damage you receive on hits. Finally, here comes the malo/insidious lines. These will reduce the resists of your enemies, and, while not really usefull at low level, later your party members will love you for them as these will allow them to be more efficient mana wise (less resist means less mana to achieve the same goal).<br>
-        Haste spells. These will allow you and your partu members to hit faster. While not as good here as an enchanteur, the shaman is still cool for that when no chantie is here.<br>
-        DoTs. We have 2 lines of DoTs : poison (act fast but will draw you a lot of aggro) and disease (slow acting, but safer. Mainly used as a solo tool as it is really slow acting and generally won’t have reach its full effect when the mob will fall).<br>
-        Utility spells. Here are what I call the travel spells (gate, bind, invisibility, levitate…), the survival tools (summon food and drink, summon a bag) and the vision spells (allow the blind race to see in dark). In this last line, my favourite one is a spell that allow you to see by the eyes of someone else (sorry, I forgot the name). It is very usefull to know what your puller brings you (as when the mob arrives, a good shaman will generally have already debuffed him and, if possible, rooted adds).<br>
-        Healing spells. While they are far from the healing capacities of a cleric, combined with slow and incapacitate line, a shaman is generally a sufficient source of heal for his team. I’ve already be main healer for secondary groups on raid (while this seems not furious, let me tell you that a PoFear brake in is nothing to laugh about) and often be primary buffer/debuffer/healer/crowd controller on groups (in these cases, let me tell you that you hardly have time to swing your weapon and you have to know your spellbook like your pocket as you often have to change your memorised spells during the action).<br>
-        Pet. When you will receive your first Dogdog life at level 34, your whole life will change. But you will have a taste of it if you hunt during your low 30’s in South Karana and charm elephants. I won’t explain why and let you the pleasure to discover it. I will only stress a point about them : do you remember when this bad mob was beating on you while you tried to gate not to die ?  Well, simply send pet, back off, gate. Voila. One advice : always keep crappy weapon to give 2 at a time to your pet, it will improve his damage output allowing him to dual wiled.<br>
-        Blind spells will act, under special circumstances, as a fear spell (provided you do not stay near the mob). This might also give you extra time to cast a gate. This spell saved my life countless times.<br>
-        Alchemy. While not being a spell line, this trading skill we receive during our mid 20’s allow us to use some effects normally not available to us (such as damage shields). But I won’t speak about it as it is really expensive (and I mean EXPENSIVE) to improve and a lot of shaman prefer have a better gear to level and improve this skill later in life.<br>
<br>
In a group :<br>
Why did people think I’m a good shaman (this word is not from me) is due to only 2 things :<br>
-        First of all, I always try to have the mob debuffed (at least slowed) before it reaches our camp, this saves the healer a lot of mana. Eventually when we have some adds, have them rooted out of the fighting place, thus taking enemies one at a time.<br>
-        Don’t be afraid to get hit. I can’t stress this enough. Why could I brake this train in KC (thanks God there were no casters in it) ? Simply because I got all mobs on me, root one, back off, root the second, back of… Then I slowed them all. Of course my mana pool was badly hurt after that, but hey, even if I was near the zoning, I didn’t want to flee without trying.<br>
It is your role to educate people about what you can do (ok, they should have search for it, but hey, not everyone has the wisdom of a shaman hehe). Be aware of what happens. Understand how your group functions. When you have understand it, 2 things are to be done. First, try to find with them out how you can improve your classes combination (here comes the importance of knowing the other’s possibilities). When this is adjusted, your group will be more efficient. Now you will have to improve it again, filling in roles that are not covered in your group. In a group, a shaman has no time to spare. When you will not debuff a mob, you will refresh a buff, heal someone, off tank a mob or swap spells. I can tell you the life of a shaman in a group is not soft <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     <br>
<br>
For the solo shaman <br>
-        Root cooking : basically root the mob and keep him dotted until it dies. When you will have a good rhythm, you will find yourself slowly cooking up to 3 or 4 mobs at a time. Though this last method is dangerous as if you run OOM (rare) or several roots brake at the same time (more often), you will find yourself in bog troubles. One variant of this is blind cooking. Instead of rooting the mob, keep him blind. This method can be dangerous has the mob can aggro some friends. I use it when I find a mob is too resistant to root spells and I am in a wide place where no add should come.<br>
-        Tanking. Yes, straight tanking ! Pull a mob with slow, incapacitate him. Possibly send a DoT in if you have too much mana compared to your HP at the end of the fight. Then tank the mob IN TEH FACE with Dogdog by your side if you have him.<br>
-        Pet kitting. This method can be tricky and I’m not sure it still works well with the last patch changes. Basically send all you can to draw a mad aggro from the mob, send pet on him and run (in external view). If well done, the mob will be crazy at you and will chase you while Dogdog kills him.<br>
-        I’m sure I forget some as our toolbox is so wide, we can do almost anything.<br>
<br>
I hope this little guide will be usefull to my young fellow and/or explain a little more about the shaman capacities for the people who group with us. In no way I want to say this is the ultimate guide (and this ain't a guide, just advices) as some fellow shaman made some really great guides (this one is a great example : <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://forums.interealms.com/shaman/showthread.php?s=&threadid=8841">forums.interealms.com/sha...eadid=8841</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> as it covers what I previously said but has more details. /bow Sneez). So feel free to add some things on your own or say me if I said BS <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
Finally, I apologise for the mistakes (f english) I could have done. Shakespeare's langage is not my native tongue, thank you to correct me <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
Feel free to contact me in game if you need more advices, I will do my best to answer you.<br>
<br>
Oh, one last thing I forgot to say : if you plan to getting your epic, think about TLC on FV so start t gather the reuired drop as soon as you can. Here we have a great advantage as we can make good xp and a few money while working on it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
